<br>
I had created, using MS Paintshop Pro, a very dandy little map. Also, I had 8x10 color'd glossy photos with write'n on the back of each one telling what each one was with dates and times on each one.<br>
<br>
I had quotes out the waazoo. It was indeed a very nice work of art! Then the shop called to tell me that my truck was ready for me to pick up...  Being Friday and all, I decided not to return to the office and complete my work-o-art. I decided what would be best would be for me to return back to my house and retire mah haunches to the Lazy-Boy.<br>
<br>
Albeit laziness, I managed to rationalize my actions with the followings excuses.... One: I didn’t want to.  Two: This is a message board for a game and I was putting way too much friggen work into it. Three: This is an opinion board and not a resource library! And Four: Are we really gonna learn anything?  I mean, we all have studied the history. We know what happened. What we debate is the righteousness of each side.  Who is right in their actions and who is wrong…<br>
<br>
When referring to &quot;98%&quot;, I was not referring only to the land deals. There were several issues that were on the table during the CDII accords. After extensive research (felt extensive anyway), I found the average consensus to be 94.5%.  According to the best resources, being the most un-bias as I could find, Israel offered 94.5% of every request / demand that Arafat had.<br>
<br>
After the CDII meetings, many opinions emerged. The main reason given for the breakdown was Jerusalem and the Temple Mound. This is the popular and prevailing reason in America. However, many upon many bias “reasons” surfaced in the following months.<br>
<br>
IMO, the only redeeming remarks that I was able to find that Arafat quoted was: “There needs to be more time to prepare and lay the groundwork for these meetings” and “…will you personally attend my funeral?”.  Both of these comments were in regards to the current Arab opinion. The arrogance of the US was that we felt as though we have already laid such groundwork in the war against Iraq. We / Clinton admin. must have thought everyone in the Arab world loved us….guess we were wrong. During the Gulf War, the information barriers, or a good portion of, came down in many counties that regulated and controlled media output….damn. <br>
<br>
Arafat’s back was in the corner (same corner as Lurikeen’s nose will be in…soon). I am guessing that he promised all or nothing although there isn’t any documentation I could find of him saying this…. It is presumed. The reason I presume this is cause he would not agree on a partial peace plan. For the exception of the refugee issue and the Temple Mount, all other issued were solved (to my knowledge). Now many feel that this was Clinton’s fault in that he wanted the glory of getting it all done…all at once. Many fell that if Clinton would have taken a little longer there might have been a considerable and comprehensive, albeit partial, peace plan in place today.<br>
<br>
Making Clinton the scapegoat is a little far-reaching. He could have requested an extension of the meetings but didn’t. However, it was Arafat that was the one who was saying all or nothing. For whatever reason’s Arafat had, he just could not accept a partial. One can only assume that this was either pride or fear of  foreign and or domestic opinion. <br>
<br>
Once Arafat returned to Palestine, he raised his arms in victory and defiance blaming Israel for not conceding and giving into Palestinian demands (documented). He began telling of how Israel wanted to regulate all boarders and basically trap Palestine by controlling all imports, exports, travel and military. All of which is documented that he accepted at the CDAII meetings.<br>
<br>
Some short time afterwards these terrorist attacks, freedom fighters, reprisals began and has been going every since in some form or fashion. Every time peace talks or cease-fire talked begin, someone blows their dumb-ass up in Israel. They tend to time this terror around these meetings and or on holy days of worship. There is no doubt that there are factions within the Arab / Muslim world that does not want Palestine to make peace with Israel. Be it inside force, outside force or Arafat himself, they just will not allow it to happen.<br>
<br>
Madaline Albright probably nailed it on the head when she said “…don’t kid yourself..these meetings are of biblical proportions …”<br>
<br>
History means everything to these people. We cannot assume a singular event or time in history and say …”It all stated when..”. All Arab and Israeli people are deeply religious. Their history and religion mean everything to them. Like most people on earth who find their god in times of despair, is it any wonder there is a religious issue at play?<br>
<br>
In regards to UN resolutions, this message board has sparked a tiny fire in my vast and boundless skull. It does frustrate the hell out of me why we call our war on terrorism a war but don’t call Israel’s war a “war”. I have begin to wonder why we call every attack on Israel a “set back to peace talks”.. Why are we so dutifully bound to mediate peace between these two groups of people? Is it because if we stop saying “peace” and start calling it a “war” we would have to enforce certain resolutions?<br>
<br>
